y when choosing a partner. And understanding externalities—the ripple of results from our actions—can clarify the if and when of having children. Michael also brings in data from the National Longitudinal Survey of Youth, a scientific sample of 18 million millennials in the United States that tracks more than a decade of young adult choices and consequences. As the survey’s longtime principal investigator and project director, Michael shows that the aggregate decisions can help us understand what might lie ahead along many possible paths—offering readers insights about how their own choices may turn out. There’s no singular formula for always making the right choice. But the adaptable framework and rich data at the heart of The Five Life Decisions will help you feel confident in whatever you decide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChoice (Psychology)xEconomic aspects. 0aChoice (Psychology)xSocial aspects. 0aDecision makingxEconomic aspects. 0aDecision makingxSocial aspects. 0aDecision making. 0aRational choice theory. 0aYoung adultszUnited StatesxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aYoung adultszUnited States. 7aSELF-HELP / General.2bisacsh  aChildren.  aChoice.  aEconomics.  aHealth.  aMarriage.  aOccupation.  aScarcity.  aSchooling.  aSovereignty.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226354583423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226354583.jpg  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles